{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.  Polynomials:  I
ntercepts and Sign.  There are several features about the graphs of po
lynomials which are important to track.  These features inform us abou
t the behavior of the function.  Those features include the following:
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "    a
.    x-intercepts of the function                   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 129 "                       Those values where the graph cr
osses the x-axis.  Those points are solutions of the equation y = f(x)
 = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    regions (intervals) i
n the domain of the function where the values of the function are posi
tive" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those reg
ions where the graph lies above the x-axis.  For a continuous function
, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the \+
intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 105 "    c.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function wh
ere the values of the function are negative" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 215 "                       Those regions where the graph lies belo
w the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polyno
mials, these regions are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to \+
+/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of \+
the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 "                       T
he value where the graph crosses the y-axis.  The value of the functio
n when x = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "    e.   end limits" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "                       For a polynomial,
 its values will become either arbitrarily large in a positive sense o
r arbitrarily large in a negative sense as the domain values tend to i
nfinity.  Graphically, the values on the graph will growth arbitrarily
 large positively (go up off the graph) or arbitrarily large negative \+
(go down off the graph) as the domain values tend to infinity.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "                       Similar behavior h
olds true for approaches to negative infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 150 "For each of the followin
g polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Choose a range tha
t will optimally represent the features of the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 
4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polynomial find each of the above fi
ve graphcial characteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = 6*x^2
+24*x-8" "6#/%\"yG,(*&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"#F(F(*&\"#CF(F*F(F(\"\")!
\"\"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
